a":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68177"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is undergoing a total laparoscopic hysterectomy for adenomyosis. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. During the procedure, while securing the uterine vessels, there is brisk arterial bleeding. The surgeon needs to identify and ligate the uterine artery while avoiding injury to surrounding structures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical course of the uterine artery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Branches from the internal iliac artery and crosses below the ureter","Branches from the external iliac artery and crosses below the ureter","Branches from the external iliac artery and crosses above the ureter","Branches from the internal iliac artery and crosses above the ureter","Branches from the common iliac artery and runs parallel to the ureter"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the anatomical relationship between the uterine artery and surrounding structures is crucial for safe gynaecological surgery. The uterine artery is a branch of the anterior division of the internal iliac artery and has an important anatomical relationship with the ureter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranches from the internal iliac artery and crosses above the ureter\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. The uterine artery originates from the anterior division of the internal iliac artery and travels medially through the base of the broad ligament. It crosses above the ureter at the level of the uterine isthmus (the \u0027ureteric bridge\u0027) before ascending along the lateral border of the uterus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranches from the external iliac artery and crosses below the ureter\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The uterine artery does not originate from the external iliac artery, which primarily supplies the lower limb.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranches from the internal iliac artery and crosses below the ureter\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While the origin is correct, the relationship with the ureter is wrong. The uterine artery crosses above, not below, the ureter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranches from the external iliac artery and crosses above the ureter\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While the relationship with the ureter is correct, the origin is wrong.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranches from the common iliac artery and runs parallel to the ureter\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The uterine artery does not originate from the common iliac artery, and it crosses the ureter rather than running parallel to it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis anatomical knowledge is essential during procedures such as hysterectomy to avoid ureteric injury. The ureter lies approximately 1.5 cm lateral to the cervix at the level of the uterine vessels, making it vulnerable during surgery if the anatomy is not well understood.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The uterine artery is a branch of the anterior division of the internal iliac artery.","The uterine artery crosses above the ureter at the level of the uterine isthmus, forming the \u0027ureteric bridge\u0027.","The ureter lies approximately 1.5 cm lateral to the cervix at the level of the uterine vessels."],"references":["Chaudhry R, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis: Uterine Arteries. [Updated 2023 Sep 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482267/#"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53634"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16997"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53634"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T14:24:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T14:25:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9687"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68177"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summar